{
  "answer": "**The work is *Vrhaspatitattva* (author unknown), Chapter 1.**[^1]\n\nThis chapter stages the described teacher-pupil dialogue between Lord Īśvara (the teacher) and the sage Vṛhaspati (the pupil). Vṛhaspati asks why the Lord \"has given so many different versions in His teachings to the host of gods? There is one called *Śaiva*, one called *Pāśupata*, one called *Alepaka*.\"[^2] The Lord's response includes the elephant-and-blind-men parable, which illustrates bewilderment over multiple scriptures (likened to the elephant's limbs) and coins the term *andhatattva* (\"principle of the blind men\") for this state.[^3]\n\nThe six blind-men comparisons, quoted verbatim:\n\n> One touched the head and said, ‘An elephant is like a **water jar**.’ Another touched the ear and said, ‘An elephant is like a **winnowing fan**.’ Another touched the trunk and said, ‘An elephant is like a **snake**.’ Another touched the belly and said, ‘An elephant is like a **granary**.’ Another touched the tail and said, ‘An elephant is like an **eel**.’ Another touched a leg and said, ‘An elephant is like a **pillar**.’[^3]\n\n[^1]: *Vrhaspatitattva*, [Chapter 1](/works/unknown-vrhaspatitattva-b60b28/01/translation/).\n\n[^2]: *Vrhaspatitattva*, [Chapter 1](/works/unknown-vrhaspatitattva-b60b28/01/translation/#p-68812c).\n\n[^3]: *Vrhaspatitattva*, [Chapter 1](/works/unknown-vrhaspatitattva-b60b28/01/translation/#p-85eacf).",
